Results of SurveyUSA Election Poll #25108
 
Pick Your Pollster, Pick Your Outcome

Either Biden, Sanders, or Warren is in Front in Delegate-Rich California, 45 Days Till Ballots Are Counted:

In the 8 most-recent public opinion polls conducted in California of likely Democratic primary voters in advance of the state's 03/03/20 Super Tuesday primary, Bernie Sanders leads in 4 of the polls, Elizabeth Warren leads in 2 of the polls, 1 poll has the contest tied and Joe Biden leads in 1 poll, this poll, conducted by SurveyUSA immediately following the 01/14/20 Democratic Party candidate debate in Iowa.

SurveyUSA has consistently shown Biden running stronger in California over the past 6 months in the nation's largest state than have other pollsters. The variability in survey results, in a state with 3 independently run, in-state research operations, shows how difficult it is in volatile 2020 to get a bead on where the contest stands at a given moment in time, much less what might happen tomorrow.

In SurveyUSA's snapshot released today, the battle for the Golden State's 415 pledged 1st-ballot convention delegates (21% of the total needed to be nominated) stands:

* Joe Biden at 30%, unchanged from SurveyUSA's last CA poll, pre-Thanksgiving.
* Elizabeth Warren and Bernie Sanders tied for 2nd place, each with 20%.
* Sanders is effectively unchanged from November; Warren is up 7 points from 13%.
* Pete Buttigieg in 4th place, far back at 8%, effectively unchanged from November.
* Mike Bloomberg, 6%, the first time SurveyUSA has included Bloomberg in a 2020 primary poll.
* Tom Steyer, 4%, up from 2% in November and from 1% in October.
* Andrew Yang, 4%, unchanged from October and November.
* Amy Klobuchar, an asterisk at 2%, where she has been in 5 consecutive CA tracking polls.

Sanders leads among CA's youngest voters, Warren leads among CA's middle-aged voters, Biden leads among seniors.

Biden in CA continues to perform well among heterogeneous CA's non-white voters: Biden today leads among Latinos, as he has in 5 consecutive SurveyUSA primary polls of the state. Biden today leads among Asian voters, 2:1 atop Warren and 3:1 atop Yang. And Biden does well among African Americans, though of potential great significance nationwide, if not necessarily in California, Biden today does not finish first among black voters for the first time this election cycle. In SurveyUSA's most recent pre-Thanksgiving poll, when United States Senator from California Kamala Harris was still actively campaigning, Harris, who is black, got 17% of the black vote, behind Biden at 32% and Sanders at 19%. Today, with CA's Harris no longer running and not offered as a choice by SurveyUSA, and black candidate Cory Booker no longer on the ballot, Sanders' support among African American voters doubles to 43%, where Sanders now leads, while Biden's support among black voters remains effectively unchanged, at 33%. Among white likely Democratic Primary voters, Biden (26%) and Warren (25%) run effectively even.

* In households with at least one LGBTQ individual, Buttigieg leads, though barely.
* In households with a child under the age of 18, Warren leads, though barely.
* In military households, Biden leads.
* In union households, Biden leads.
* Among independents, who are eligible to vote in CA's primary, Sanders leads.
* Among voters with a high-school education, Biden edges Sanders 4:3.
* Among voters with a 4-year college degree, Biden and Warren run effectively even.
* Among those who attend religious services regularly, Biden leads decisively.
* Among Catholics, Biden leads Sanders 2:1.
* Among Protestants, Biden leads Sanders 3:2.
* In greater Los Angeles, there is clear separation between Biden (31%), Sanders (24%) and Warren (18%).
* But in the Bay Area, the contest is a 3-way tie.

21% of CA likely Democratic Primary voters say the Democratic nominee will be known by March, perhaps as soon as the day the CA primary ballots are counted. But a plurality, 25%, say the party's nominee will not be chosen until the week of the Democratic National Convention, mid-July, in Milwaukee, 6 months from now.

About: SurveyUSA interviewed 2,400 adults statewide 01/14/20 through 01/16/20, immediately following the Democratic Party candidate debate 01/14/20 in Iowa. Of the adults, 1,967 are registered to vote. Of the registered voters, SurveyUSA determined that 565 are likely to return a ballot on or before Super Tuesday. Ballots will be mailed to CA vote-by-mail voters in 2 weeks. This research was conducted online. According to the polling-aggregator websites FiveThirtyEight.com and RealClearPolitics.com: the CA-based Public Policy Institute of California released a CA poll 01/13/20 with Sanders up by 3 points; CA-based Capitol Weekly released a poll 01/09/13 with Sanders up by 3 points; Capitol Weekly released a poll 12/23/19 with Warren up by 3; NPR released a poll 12/16/19 with Sanders up by 3; Capitol Weekly released a poll 12/13/19 with Warren up 4 by; CNN released a poll 12/11/19 that characterized CA as a 3-way tie; the Los Angeles Times released a poll 12/05/19 with Sanders up by 2. The last CA poll to have Joe Biden in 1st place was released 11/26/19 by SurveyUSA of New Jersey. YouGov and Quinnipiac have not polled CA since July 2019.
